statement.p:
An L-shaped triomino is a 2 \times 2 tile with one square missing. It looks like this:



\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=.25] %mathbook width=20%
\draw (0,0) -- (0,2) -- (2,2) -- (2,1)--  (0,1) -- cycle;
\draw (0,0) -- (1,0) -- (1,2);
\end{tikzpicture}








 Consider the following 4 \times 4 checkerboards with one square missing (shown in black). For each board, show that you can cover the rest of the squares using L-shaped triominoes.




\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=.5] %mathbook width=80%
\begin{scope}

\foreach \x in {0,1,2,3,4}
{
\draw (0,\x) -- (4,\x);
\draw (\x,0) -- (\x,4);
}

\fill (0,0) -- (0,1) -- (1,1) -- (1,0) -- cycle;

\end{scope}


\begin{scope}[shift={(8,0)}]

\foreach \x in {0,1,2,3,4}
{
\draw (0,\x) -- (4,\x);
\draw (\x,0) -- (\x,4);
}

\fill (2,2) -- (3,2) -- (3,3) -- (2,3) -- cycle;

\end{scope}



\begin{scope}[shift={(16,0)}]

\foreach \x in {0,1,2,3,4}
{
\draw (0,\x) -- (4,\x);
\draw (\x,0) -- (\x,4);
}

\fill (1,3) -- (1,4) -- (2,4) -- (2,3) -- cycle;

\end{scope}


\end{tikzpicture}











 Now consider the following 8 \times 8 checkerboard with one square missing (shown in black). Show that you can cover the rest of the squares using L-shaped triominoes as follows (and shown in the right diagram below). (1) Place your first triomino in the gray squares as shown. (2) Use part (a) to fill in the four 4 \times 4 sub-boards.





\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=.5] %mathbook width=80%



\begin{scope}



\foreach \x in {0,1,2,3,4,5,6,7,8}
{
\draw (0,\x) -- (8,\x);
\draw (\x,0) -- (\x,8);
}

\fill (6,2) -- (6,3) -- (7,3) -- (7,2) -- cycle;

\end{scope}



\begin{scope}[shift={(12,0)}]


\fill[gray!33] (3,3) -- (4,3) -- (4,4) -- (5,4) -- (5,5) -- (3,5) -- cycle;

\foreach \x in {0,1,2,3,4,5,6,7,8}
{
\draw (0,\x) -- (8,\x);
\draw (\x,0) -- (\x,8);
}

\fill (6,2) -- (6,3) -- (7,3) -- (7,2) -- cycle;

\draw [very thick] (4,0) -- (4,8);
\draw [very thick] (0,4) -- (8,4);

\end{scope}

\end{tikzpicture}










 Reflect on how you solved the 8 \times 8 problem by  turning it into four instances of 4 \times 4 problems. Then go back to your answers in part (a) and show how you solved each 4 \times 4 problem by turning it into four instances of 2 \times 2 problems.







 If I gave you a 16 \times 16 checkerboard with one square missing, could you cover the rest with L-shaped triominoes? How would you do it?







 Use induction to prove the following statement:




For n \geq 1, any 2^n \times 2^n checkerboard with one square missing can be covered by L-shaped dominoes.










 Base Case: What is your base case?









 Inductive Hypothesis: State your inductive hypothesis for n.









  Inductive Step:  Write down what you want to SHOW for n+1. Then try to find "a copy of the size n problem" in the size n+1 problem.
Rearrange and use your inductive hypothesis to prove the result!
